                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Richmond</placeName>
                                        <date>Sept 4, 1852</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Friend!</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">By the favourable oppor-<lb/>tunity afforded by
                                        our friend <persName>Mr Mailert</persName><lb/> leaving for
                                        your place, I drop you<lb/> a few lines hoping that they
                                        may<lb/> meet you in the enjoyment of that<lb/>
                                                  vigo<del>u</del>rous state of mind which the
                                        al-<lb/>mighty has for years past endowed<lb/> you with. My
                                        health during<lb/> this summer has been much enfeebled<lb/>
                                        but thank God I am much impro-<lb/>ved.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I read your last no of the<lb/> “Occident” with
                                        much delight, your<lb/> views as to the wants of our
                                        people<lb/> could not have been better portrayed,<lb/> the
                                        question is, how can it be spee-<lb/>dily accomplished, year
                                        after year<lb/> has glided away since your noble<lb/> scheme
                                        of a convention has been pro-<lb/>posed. If that cannot be
                                        effected, we<lb/> can do nothing, as that scheme has laid<lb/>
                                        <sic>dorment</sic> so long, and as the New Yorkers<lb/> are
                                        so jealous on any subject that does<lb/> not originate with
                                        them, could we not</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>get them to make a new move in the matter,<lb/> let them have the
                                        honor and the glory of<lb/> reviving the subject, something
                                        must be<lb/> done.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">“Our Ritual and its Recital” has claimed<lb/> much
                                        notice here as also <persName>Mr Eckman's</persName>
                                        ar-<lb/>ticle, they contain stubborn facts and they<lb/>
                                        must be remedied, I often wished that<lb/> some reformation
                                        could be made in the<lb/> recital of our ritual, my
                                        principal, and<lb/> instructions that I have invariably
                                        given<lb/> to our hazanim here has been, “that<lb/> every
                                        portion of the device that is read<lb/> in the synagogue
                                        should be read in<lb/> a slow, distinct and impressive
                                        manner<lb/> irregardless of the time that it occupies,”<lb/>
                                        if the Form of Service is too long for to be<lb/> recited in
                                        that manner in reasona-<lb/>ble length of time, steps should
                                        be taken<lb/> to have them curtailed by omitting all<lb/>
                                        <sic>repititions</sic>, The Catholics have their<lb/> “Three
                                        hail Mary's &amp;c” it is not necessary<lb/> for us to have
                                        these repetitions.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Only look at the Kipur service where<lb/>
                                                  “<add>?</add>” are repeated so often. “El
                                        Meleck<lb/> yosheb” is rattled away ridiculous and<lb/> so
                                        it goes through the whole of the ser-<lb/>vice the Question
                                        arises, how are our<lb/> children to learn to say their
                                        prayers</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>with that devotion necessary for the recital of<lb/> our sublime
                                        ritual, it gives the high min-<lb/>ded adult a distaste for
                                        the service, now<lb/> contrast our service with that of the
                                        gentiles<lb/> only see how decorous every part of their<lb/>
                                        service is performed. When you enter into<lb/> some of their
                                        churches we are struck with<lb/> awe we are reminded often
                                        with the solemn<lb/> scriptural injunction of “the Lord is
                                        in this<lb/> holy Temple let all the earth keep
                                        si-<lb/>lence before Him.”</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">There must be something done to stimu-<lb/>late
                                        this lukewarmness existing amongst<lb/> our Co-religionists,
                                        had I but the power<lb/> to <sic>weild</sic> the pen and
                                        give vent my fee<lb/>lings in this matter.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I am aware that any attempt to ab-<lb/>ridge our
                                        form of service would meet<lb/> with opposition at first,
                                        but as it is<lb/> not the old mosaic or Temple form of<lb/>
                                        service I see no good reason why the<lb/> change cannot be
                                        made to suit the<lb/> country &amp; times in which we live.
                                        I wish we<lb/> had but one minhag in
                                                  <placeName>America</placeName>, and the<lb/>
                                        service read in good grammatical Hebrew,<lb/> any thing that
                                        I in my feeble efforts can<lb/> effect, God knows I am
                                        willing to<lb/> do, hoping to hear soon. I remain yours
                                        &amp;c</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">
                                        <persName role="author">Jacob Ezekiel</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">
                                        <placeName>Pa</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p>Favd by</p>
                              <p>
                                        <persName>Mr A. Mailert</persName>
                              </p>
